DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       Many  users tend to copy data around a lot. So it may happen that a lot
       duplicates old  tmpfiles  or  whatsoever  are  lurking  around  on  the
       Harddsik. Rmlint is a tool to remove those files automagically.

       It  is  especially useful if you're getting crazy because you need 20MB
       more to save that film.

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       -h --help
              Display a short helptext.

       -v --verbosity <v>
              Sets the verbosity level to <v> Where: 0 prints nothing 1 prints
              only errors 2 prints warning 3 prints everything

       -t --threads <t>
              Set the number of threads to <t> used in full checksum creation.

       -p  --paranoid
              Do a byte-by-byte comparasion additionally.

       -d  --maxdepth <depth>
              Only recurse up to this depth. (default: inf)

       -f --followlinks
              Wether links are followed (None is reported twice)

       -s --samepart
              Never cross mountpoints, stay on the same partition

       -m --mode <m>
              Tell rmlint how to deal with the files it finds.

              Where modes are:

              list  - Only list found files and exit.

       link  - Replace file with a hard link to original.

       ask   - Ask for each file what to do

       noask - Full removal without asking.

       cmd   - Takes the command given by -c and executes it on the file.


       -c --command <cmd>
              Execute  a  shellcommand  on found files when used with '-m cmd'
              Example: rmlint -m cmd -c "ls -lah %s %s" First  %s  expands  to
              found duplicate, second to original.

       -r --fregex <pat>
              Checks filenames against the pattern <pat>

       -R --dregex <pat>
              Checks dirnames against the pattern <pat>

       -i --invmatch
              Invert match - Only investigate when npt containing <pat>

       -e --matchcase
              Matches case of paths (not by default)


